ElementDescription: During the past 6 months, how many times did (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) go to an emergency room or emergency department for (your own physical or mental/their own) own health issues? This includes emergency room visits that did or did not result in a hospital admission.
Notes: 1= 0 times; 2= 1 time; 3= 2-3 times; 4= 4 or more times

ElementDescription: During the past 6 months, how many times were (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) hospitalized (stayed in the hospital overnight for at least two nights, for your/their own health issues)
Notes: 1= 0 times; 2= 1 time; 3= 2-3 times; 4= 4 or more times

ElementDescription: Do (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) have a primary care provider? Primary care providers (or ''PCPs'') are physicians, nurse practitioners, or physician's assistants. Sometimes people call their primary care provider their ''general doctor''. They evaluate and treat new medical problems, manage chronic illnesses, help people prevent medical problems, and make referrals to other specialists, as needed. Primary care providers are usually trained in family practice, internal medicine, or pediatrics, but they may be trained in other specialties, such as gynecology.
Notes: 1= Yes; 2= No; 3= I do not know

ElementDescription: About when was (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) last healthcare visit with (your/their) primary care provider?
Notes: 1= Less than 6 months ago; 2= About 6 months to a year ago; 3= About 1 to 3 years ago; 4= More than 3 years ago; 5= I do not think (Direct Report: I / Caregiver Report: they) have ever had a visit with (my/their) primary care provider

ElementDescription: In general, do you think that (Direct Report: your primary care provider knows you are / Caregiver Report: their healthcare providers know they are) autistic (or, if you/they do not have a formal diagnosis, that you/they identify as autistic)?
Notes: 1= Yes, I am pretty sure they do (for example, we have discussed it or I have seen it in my/their medical records); 2= Probably (for example, I assume it is in my/their records, but we have not discussed it); 3= No (for example, I/they have chosen not to tell providers and it isnï¿½t in my/their records); 4= I do not know

ElementDescription: Have (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) had a healthcare visit with a mental health provider (such as a psychiatrist, psychologist, or therapist) in the last 6 months?

Have (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: they) had healthcare visits with any other doctors, nurse practitioners, or physician's assistants in the last 6 months? Do not include healthcare providers (you/they) saw while (you/they) were in an emergency room or while (you/they) were hospitalized.
(Direct Report: How often do you / Caregiver Report: Do they) need support from someone to get (health care/medical care)?
Notes: 1= Always or often; 2= Sometimes; 3= Rarely or never

ElementDescription: How often do (Direct Report: you / Caregiver Report: you think they) get the support (you need for/they need to get) health care?
Notes: 1= Always or often; 2= Sometimes; 3= Rarely or never

ElementDescription: Think about (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) office visits with doctors, nurses, or other healthcare professionals (e.g., nurse practitioners, physician's assistants, counselors, therapist, dentists, psychologists, optometrist, etc.). Do (you/they) usually talk with them, or do they usually communicate in other ways? For example, do (you/they)  usually sign, use pictures, use an interpreter, or use a speech device to communicate with them?)
Notes: 1 = Talk; 2 = Something else; 3 = N/A (For example, I/they do not communicate with healthcare providers at all)

ElementDescription: Think about (Direct Report: your / Caregiver Report: their) office visits with doctor, nurses, or other healthcare professionals. How much help do (you/they) get from (your/their) supporters to communicate with providers?
Notes: 1= (Direct Report: I / Caregiver Report: They) usually communicate with providers (myself/themselves); 2= (I/they) mostly communicate with providers (myself/themselves), but someone helps (me/them) some of the time; 3 = Someone besides (me/them) does most or all of the communication
